===Etymology===
"Haydar's city" or "lion city", from haydar (lion) and ābād (city) {{suffix|haydar|abad|lang=en}}. It was named to honour the [[Caliph]] [[Ali Ibn Abi Talib]], who was also known as Haydar because of his lion-like valour in battles.<ref name="Everett-Heath2005">Everett-Heath, John. ''Concise Dictionary of World Place Names'', Oxford University Press, 2005 p&nbsp;223 ({{ISBN|978-0-19-860537-9}})</ref>

<references />

